## Content
````
The document `0009-support-long-running-operations.md` provides a detailed design plan for integrating long-running operations into the Agent Framework and MEAI chat clients. The central focus of the design is to enable both synchronous and asynchronous interaction patterns, particularly for complex AI tasks that require significant processing time such as code generation, reasoning, and content processing. The document outlines various options and decisions for supporting these operations, including necessary interfaces, methods, and model changes.

The design introduces several ways to handle long-running operations for chat clients through the `IChatClient` and `IAsyncChatClient` interfaces. The primary method for supporting long-running tasks is the introduction of `GetResponseAsync` and `GetStreamingResponseAsync` methods that can handle starting operations, retrieving status and results, and updating operations as needed. The document proposes using the existing method structure while adding new interfaces for uncommon operations like cancellation and deletion. This modular design ensures extensibility and minimizes disruptions to existing codebases by not implementing breaking changes.

The document also highlights different configurations for enabling long-running operations such as per invocation or per chat client instance, allowing flexibility to developers. It presents a structured comparison of existing APIs (OpenAI, Azure AI Foundry, and A2A) and their management of long-running operations, including streaming capabilities. A detailed section discusses how to initiate operations, handle status and results, and manage execution modes, proposing a unified continuation token model for better consistency across different implementations.

Additionally, the design addresses agent clients through the `AIAgent` class and proposes using the existing `Run{Streaming}Async` methods for common long-running operations, with new methods for uncommon operations like cancellation and deletion. It provides multiple approaches to manage execution modes and propose using custom types for continuation tokens to encapsulate properties that represent a long-running operation across various models. The plan mandates a requirement for threads in long-running operations to ensure agent responses are consistently captured, ensuring seamless integration when server-side and client-side managed threads interact within long-running use cases.

Overall, the document establishes a comprehensive, versatile framework for integrating long-running operations into AI agent and chat client architectures, leveraging existing structures while promoting scalability, extensibility, and developer-friendly interfaces.
````
